Daily menu of an obese child: not breakfast and dinner stuffed
Over one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9 per cent of the school population and obesity at 5 per cent.
Obese children come in most families with a lifestyle that is not healthy, according to current research.
It shows again the importance of the environment where it grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessive children are fed, for example, of sausages at least twice as often as children of normal weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of obese people had eaten fried potatoes the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a chance."
In overweight families there is no practice of sports, which applies to most current families, where only 15 per cent of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last year's school year and participated in it almost 900 children of Basic Education from all Czech Republic.
It was already the second edition of the "Obesity of not a chance" program, which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th course.
A proper diet and a sufficient amount of family exercise are determining factors, which significantly decrease the number of overweight and even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals per day according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet," says one of the survey results.
No breakfast but with sausage for dinner
The specialists warn that, in healthy development, the details are also important, which they also count, such as having a fixed time for family breakfast.
In Czech Republic, however, only 23 per cent of schoolchildren's families had breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each has breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that 10% of households didn't have breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in obese children's families there is much more frequent use of fries.
Almost all - regardless of weight - drink sweet refreshments daily (70%).
As a rule, they do sport over 40 per cent of the children surveyed, but among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15 per cent.
Make your diet
The next phase of the study enabled the chosen children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12-15 years, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far removed from the ideal."
Among their favourite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
"It is especially alarming the popularity of sweets," is warned in the final report of the study.
As a main meal, you take the palm to the pasta and follow the meat closely.
Practically, children always reject legumes and taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Switch to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive fair information.
"In the control group of the study participants, who completed the questionnaire after the completion of the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence," an important change was made in many cases in favour of the principles of healthy eating," is pointed out in the study's results.
It draws attention, for example, to sweet drinks, where many children would begin to prefer normal and common water.
Children would also more often choose bird meat and fish for the main meal in the questionnaire and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
