How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time sold in most cases only to the socialist bloc, because the trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went from holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime bowed west and the Czech tourists' trips were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but one had to queue with a sleeping bag and spend it all night, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "change promise" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a change guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their vacations in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs would acquire. This custom still persists.
The way the Czechs travel has suffered from a genuine revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which today we are no longer aware, that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not be travelled freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa exemptions were imposed for travel to the neighbouring States of Western Europe, resulting in an enormous wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see a lot of trips to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech groups were sleeping in the parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs at that time was to take the food with them (conservations, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it average wages, which around 1997 resulted in an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare trips using charter flight connections, which made the prices of travel incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90s of the last century, the Czechs were already travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism was already in 2000, when the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and it went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights depart every year with Czech tourists made distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, so our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, spent more than 15 thousand Czech crowns per head on trips abroad, including expenses at the place of stay.
