Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted that he had been killed in Norway in July, who left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to log on to Facebook.
"We realized that it wasn't so hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on European digital populism by the British DEMOS study centre.
Facebook's personal information range is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic features with scientific accuracy - the way sellers have been using it for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then directed advertisements, but instead of linking them to a new dietary band or product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
"It's a totally new way of doing an investigation," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online advocates of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry with immigration.
However, in a kind of turn, "those who combine their activism in line with off-line activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "Like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "supernova data" is generating a rise in research, driving the number of academic papers with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you tried to poll people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You should go through the party, and they would never allow you access," says Bartlett.
"Facebook eliminates all that -- you go to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr Megan Moreno, from Wisconsin University and her colleagues, found that university students who spoke about their drunken facets on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who publishes too many state updates with their drunkards.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, the co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Child Research Institute, said the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who otherwise would not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "hitting" its own population to obtain data.
The Site Data Team has developed statistics on the status of the relationship and the Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the mid-term of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information to which it can be accessed - digital freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make available to others its large amount of research data).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching, liking or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
