Congressman for New York and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made the ridicule with his scorned quickly rebuffed by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with infractions in the financing of the campaign related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term on his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have provided the exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Men who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades in prestigious universities that carried out research projects in depth, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been refuted.
Liars do look in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stutter, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years investigating scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps to navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "minders oriented towards themselves", while women say more lies "oriented towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their couples than those who are not married (but lies that they usually say tend to be "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called creating a baseline.
Helps to provide benchmarks to measure later the changes.
Observe the posture of the subject, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's better that you know if someone normally hits with his foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when he sees his feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal and non-verbal behavioural groups.
Consider these groups of behaviour as signals of alarm, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their history, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change their posture significantly, or display a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all difficult questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely show that the interview is over just to look for that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson shoved his leg to the bottom and used his past time as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I... understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
