According to the data presented by the PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, still without counting the votes corresponding to 879 out of the 6 thousand 74 total records.
The possibility of the "vote by vote" is a reality regarding the electoral process of this year in Michoacán, where according to the data presented by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 out of the 6,000 74 total records.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or Electoral Code of the State or its Electoral Justice Act, since the Congress of the State passed the reforms shortly before the completion of the legal period so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for in the Official Journal of the State Act, with the argument that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local legislative power and called the vote of the state representative to constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal" since he has no right to "sanction or veto".
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the EMI it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may take place on the assumption that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and enforcement in the record of the box or does not open in the possession of the President of the box; or, where there are errors or obvious alterations in the records.
In addition, the total counting of the vote received in all boxes of the election may be made where there is evidence that the difference between the alleged candidate winner of the election in question and the candidate who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the party's representative and/or coalition that applied to the second of the nominees.
The total counting of the vote may also be carried out if, at the end of the ordinary period, the difference between the alleged successful candidate and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of partial counting are excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation there is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is just 0.16 percent, although without accounting for the votes of 129 out of the 923 total records.
