The new Monti Government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a devastating new attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure in Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
It will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of the Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about whether the new Prime Minister will succeed.
To rescue Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
