When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we take a while from not playing, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we could have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they're celebrating 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything they've achieved?
Yeah, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us would think we'd be in a big rock band and have done it for over 20 years now that it looks like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and are very moved that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we love creating music.
We're lucky to go to places in the world we always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of big gangs.
We are very friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a movement comes from a group of friends and it's a rare thing.
From time to time, a city gang comes up, but it's a lot weirder when five or ten bands come out at the same time from the same city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still played with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on his tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them still and we're honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It is also very strange that a band like yours will stick together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) has joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much longer than many bands last.
First of all, I think we are all lucky to be alive and, secondly, we all care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, musical avenues have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experience.
We trusted each other with each other's music and could not be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; yet, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance sheet?
As we've been growing up, it's been easier to find a balance sheet.
We make sure not to be too on tour because it is easy to fall into that game of the great crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for music, that reminds you that you must respect music and what brought it to you, without becoming enthralled by being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never published a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were many frustrations because it would last so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think about the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know your work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose it for the opening?
Yes, production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we're looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do they always change Yellow Ledbetter's letter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that happens to him.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
They're so many.
Among the first things that happen to me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunge relevant despite being no longer a fashion?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time, and, if there's any relevance now, I think it's something wonderful because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are doing now better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and has now become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that might look lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs though they can sound a little positive.
With both of them, when Ed touched me, I cried when I heard them and they were deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs certainly represent that for me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
