Visual flight:
In accordance with aeronautical regulations, the flight was conducted under visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports at the AICM were suitable for take-off, as the aircraft moves towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, low cloud layers were presented.
Selected paths:
As a result of the cloud conditions, the crew are likely to have sought a lower elevation and increased visibility of the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of remnants of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred in a straight and side-by-side trajectory.
The aircraft remnant scatter pattern suggests that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
Evidence in the ship's remnants of some kind of explosion or fire remains undisclosed on the site of the sinister.
The latest results of the research indicate that there may have been multiple contact with the ground.
During the fieldwork, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9 thousand 200 feet above the middle sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was likely to disarticulate along the route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After the thorough search in a wider area than the arranged site, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Leads Social Security research to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Childhood Obesity and Adolescents' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Biochemistry Unit of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research is invited to participate to the population whether right or not, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m..
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day, he stated that the goal was to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific feeding questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and hereditary history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger suffering such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that on Saturdays all participants were subjected to anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (the aim was to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is the concern of health professionals for the alarming increase in weight in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity among children and 47 per cent of girls; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed', said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexico has 65 percent Indian American heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows for the detection of any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, and the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are told each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain the majority of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, hamburger, et cetera) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM Asphalt would avoid kisses
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 berries each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the berries could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the berries, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to that of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and hence the formation of berries.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, high molecular weight molecules, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called Maltese, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes cracked, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is changing during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist warned in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, pointed, is bathed with asphalt.
As vehicles are transited and efforts are generated, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If modified asphalt were to be spread even better, the chemical engineer was of the opinion.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, is placed a last layer called a treadmill, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
As the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the treadmill also requires the appropriate thickness and the material that is made should be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground is moistened, the water is spread inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of tanks.
In the process of formation of a bach, he said, the first to wear out is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of tanks and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the floor should always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, in order to avoid the frequent formation of tanks.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and allow to repair the tanks with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
