With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls for Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Canadian society lives by denying death.
In fact, only 9 per cent of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they wish to die and make arrangements to do so.
It is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Penal Code in a way that allows assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient raises this option and has been tried competently to make the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada occupies the tenth place, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, as indicated by experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And even though most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this respect is recorded in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive topic of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or not constituted a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-competent persons or that they have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide were not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
We recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia, since they believe it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66 per cent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not lead to less value in the lives of the elderly or disabled.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that a process should not be initiated against them.
In relation to the maintenance or interruption of a patient's health care, the situation is not so clear, as reported by the authors of the report.
Furthermore, its recommendations suggest that it is indicated in the Penal Code that withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The expert committee also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses assistance at the end of his or her life without fear of facing a complaint.
With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls for Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered euthanasia and undergoes the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their reservations regarding the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described as "extreme" the position of the experts who sign the report, among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to the terminally ill.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 can ask for help to commit suicide," says Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr. Deschamps also stressed that the authors of the report seemed to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations."
Health Law Specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the findings of the report, which called "manifesto in favor of euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, puts into question especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
