Austria
Introduction of a "gold rule" budget in the Constitution
The Government of the Great Social Democratic/Democratic Coalition which is in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a budget "gold rule" to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible degradation of Austria's sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when Austrian government debt reaches 74.6%, a figure far above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency was reduced at one level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay €3 billion more in interest every year," said Deputy Christian Democratic Foreign Affairs Chancellor Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responded to a request from the Brussels Summit to the countries members of the euro area on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, by the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in an Act of equivalent value.
The approach adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
Before 2017, the structural government deficit should decrease annually by 0.75 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP) and, as of 2017, the structural government deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35 per cent of GDP each year, while regional States, as well as the communes, should submit balanced budgets.
The objective is to reduce public debt by 2020/2021 under the 60% criterion laid down in the Maastricht Treaty.
