Energy policy:
the facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting should be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will be useful only if it looks at all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will lead to the duplication of electricity demand by 2050, unless a large part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be addressed to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The accident in Fukushima does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
That is not the case either with Belgium, which is subject to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or with Switzerland, which is solely aimed at building state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, for example, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a discourse.
Berlin's election is going to be an increase in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, particularly from Russia, for increasing CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noted.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
Europe's wind champion, of which 30% of its electricity is obtained, is also one of the big users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are 65% and 50% higher respectively than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the record of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% electricity bill higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and ensuring the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe's cheapest electricity.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would be realistic in the wonderful declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not show opposition in principle to that kind of energy, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 leading jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets that can create non-removable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear power, it would be the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion annually in French nuclear equipment and services exports.
What electrician would run an EPR designed to run sixty years when your manufacturer's collapse is planned?
In order to solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, as there is no diabolical source.
Areva's development of low-carbon solutions, nuclear and renewable, demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing power stations and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it had no consequences for either the people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the reactor design and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unparalleled natural disasters, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While studying it all the electric actors who want to build a power plant, the interruption of their construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow partisan emotions, dogmas and manoeuvres to dominate such an important debate for our country's economic, social and financial situation.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France's "country of human rights".
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) claiming from the past that France "needs no foreign talents, workers or waiters."
However, it is rarely considered from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this subject, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has nearly two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone made Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over the whole misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-development will help solve the "problem of migration".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be cost-effective electorally, but it is economically expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly those with low qualifications, by pressing to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and primarily engage in professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A Positive Impact on Wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants results in the arrival of nationals having a positive impact on the wages and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migratory flows represents an increase in real wages over the long term between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants provide contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they provide an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income less expenditure) of EUR 150,000 to the average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it has to think only of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember that, although it was invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, from Napoleon the Little One, that this was something that was thought of.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot used to say.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The paleondy of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a twofold revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return from the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now moved and in many cases the Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly way.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a stop to the void of the nationalist hole: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take effect, but a common, full, peaceful and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to finish the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is one that bends to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, which suffers from their powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for people's sovereignty to regain the momentum of the European project.
Because only together can Europeans reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investments.
The departure from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be made without total democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
