The North Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which communicates directly Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a big pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, in the opening of North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly under the sea Russia with Germany.
Simbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the valve steering wheel that controls the Russian gas entry into the Western Europe network together.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first one had 1,224 km that communicates the region of St Petersburg with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipe should be completed by the end of 2012 which will allow to supply a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this huge work presents the airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it by closing access to markets in Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, since the project has generated a gap between the Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us in an organic way," said François Fillon during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the Gazprom directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine pipe is made of cement coated steel to protect it against the anchors of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream society.
Measures to protect fauna and flora were also necessary.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project's leaders gave up the control platform when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish permanently on the sea facing their shores.
"In case of failure, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller needs.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released to the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that there will be a leak, as they have planned joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the status of the pipeline is guaranteed by an underwater robot, carried out by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the form of a pure, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full journey days at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without any need for repair.
The gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined her.
These five companies have set up a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and exploit the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, the entire capacity of gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," Jens Müller says.
The financing of the pipeline was completed by 30 per cent with the contributions of the shareholders and 70 per cent with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
The total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an adventurous air, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine Book is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine's notebooks with the present appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at that time to release to the market a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The book is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (top skin), which refers to a barnized cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far away has been the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, with open spirit and cults.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its inceptions, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are seeking employment.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons doubled the average rate: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made for 15 years has been considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there's still a lot to be done."
It should be mentioned that disabled persons continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (a 17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% has not finished the bachelor's degree and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the quid of the problem", says Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreprer para la Cité association noted that the surveyed directors have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, an objective that was laid down in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the establishment number "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies holding between 20 and 49 workers have employees with disabilities in their staff, compared with 82 per cent of companies with 100 to 199 workers.
